    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be a nitrogen thing. how do i check if the soil ph is actually affecting how much nitrogen they can get? like is there a specific way to test it or fix it if it's off?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You'll need a soil pH testing kit or a digital meter to get an accurate reading of your soil's acidity or alkalinity. Most tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH, ideally between 6.0 and 6.8, which is where nitrogen is most available to them. If your pH is too high or too low, you can make adjustments by adding elemental sulfur to lower the pH, or using lime to raise it. Remember, these changes take time, so don't expect instant results; you'll need to monitor it over several weeks.",
